title: For Sale/Trade:  Trijicon TA41-NLAW-CW rare 2.5x20 ACOG / missile launcher sight with MM07 base
postcontent: Good day, For sale is a rather uncommon, possibly even "rare" ACOG. This is a model TA41-NLAW-CW, a 2.5x20 ACOG designed exclusively for the NLAW anti-tank missile launcher. The TA41-NLAW-CW is unique mostly in the fact that it is built on a unique 2.5x20 chassis that is not offered by Trijicon in any other way shape or form. The reticule on the scope is an inverted 'V', probably as a reminder to strike armored targets from the top. The tip of the 'V' is illuminated with Trijicon's famous dual-illumination system. I have no way to date this particular sight, but the Tritium is still "burning", and visible in darkness. There is a rubber eyepiece on the aperture of the sight, but it can be removed very easily (just held on with mild adhesive) to give you the standard peripheral vision. Lastly, the ACOG has special markings on the left side and bottom, not common to other ACOGs. The base of this sight is compatible with Trijicon's "special ring" mounting systems. Trijicon has since discontinued this mounting system, but mounts are still readily available. I am including on brand new MM07 mount (realistically, a $75-100 value) with this, a low-height adapter for picatinny rails. About a dozen other mounts are available elsewhere otherwise. These sights are used as optics on the MBT-LAW / NLAW missile launchers, used in the Untied Kingdom, Finald, Luxembourg, and Sweden. This ACOG normally folds up into the body of the launcher on a special bracket. The NLAW launchers are single-shot devices, and disposed of after firing. About 18 months ago I had the opportunity to get one of these sights (pictured) from an un-claimed freight auction. I have been using it on a SBR Beretta CX4 Storm in 9mm for the past 17 months, with no issues. It is resistant to water, hot & cold temperatures, recoil, and everything else you would expect from a legendary ACOG. It tracks well, and holds it's zero perfectly. The glass is every bit as crisp as you would expect from any other ACOG (trust me, I have owned 6 others). *This particular* sight should be brand new. They come in plain cardboard boxes with generic foam inserts. No manual, no mount, no frills. Just a label on the outside with a serial number. ...despite me telling you this, I do not have the box available for *this* one I am selling. They ship from the factory with the turrets both at their extreme outside positions, and must be turned in once prior to being used (I just did it on this one). They also come with a generic warning sticker on the side of the objective, but this (and it's residual adhesive) was removed. It has not been shot yet. Add a fun, functional, and unique optic to your collection! Shipping will be actual cost to US only via USPS. Insurance is available at exact cost, should you opt for it.Thank you for looking!

Silver nitride finish steel receiver with high-relief engraving, polished blued barrels, and oil finish grade II/III walnut, standard Invector choke tubes. What makes White Lightning? The term "left in the white", or simply "white" has been used for decades describing the color of shotgun and rifle parts. "In the white" means that firearm parts were not blued or color case-hardened or colored in any way, but left in the natural, polished color of the metal, such as steel. Often times, the bolt, top lever, slide, ejectors and other parts are left in the natural color of the metal, providing a luxurious contrast to the rest of the shotgun. In this way, the Browning's Citori White Lightning receiver and action offer a fine choice as opposed to "blued" over-unders. But don't be afraid that the steel receiver is unprotected: the natural color steel receiver and trigger guard are protected from corrosion by a durable coating process called a "nitrided" finish, offering similar protection to bluing. Just with a uniquely elegant and attractive look. A well-rounded pistol grip for performance. The Citori White Lightning's round knob or pistol grip allows the shooter to position his hand at the same, solid place for each shot, thus offering better control for fast-flying waterfowl upland game, sporting clays or trap and skeet. Matching the rounded pistol grip is the forearm. It is nicely rounded and together, they give the name to this over under gun as "Lightning Style," or the Citori White Lightning, a classic style indeed, a timeless style.
